      <abstract>
        <p>A 28-year-old female was transferred to the emergency department from her physician&#x2019;s office for further evaluation of tachycardia. She was being seen for a recent illness which included nausea, vomiting, diarrhea and fevers. The patient endorsed fatigue, dyspnea on exertion, and extremity edema. She had no chest pain or cough. Exam revealed a pale, fatigued, mildly ill-appearing female with bilateral lower extremity edema and diminished breath sounds on the right. Chest radiograph revealed a large right pleural effusion (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="f1-wjem-15-123">Figure 1</xref>). Computed tomographic angiography of the chest was performed (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="f2-wjem-15-123">Figure 2</xref>).</p>
      </abstract>
